<DocsLayout
  title="Built-in tools"
  eyebrow="Capabilities"
  description="The standard tool surface gode ships with."
  prev={{ href: "/docs/providers/", title: "Providers" }}
  next={{ href: "/docs/mcp/", title: "MCP integration" }}
>
  <p>
    gode ships a broad initial set of coding tools. They live under
    <code>internal/godex/tools/builtin</code> and are registered into the same tool registry
    as MCP-exposed tools — providers see them through one uniform interface.
  </p>

  <h2>The set</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>shell</strong> — execute commands in the workspace, with stdout/stderr streamed as events.</li>
    <li><strong>files</strong> — read, list, and stat files inside the workspace.</li>
    <li><strong>edit</strong> — targeted in-place file edits with explicit before/after strings.</li>
    <li><strong>patch</strong> — apply unified diffs across one or more files in a single call.</li>
    <li><strong>search</strong> — fast text search across the workspace.</li>
    <li><strong>git</strong> — git status/log/diff/branch operations as structured tool calls.</li>
    <li><strong>lsp</strong> — Language Server Protocol bridge for symbol-aware operations.</li>
    <li><strong>mcp</strong> — invoke tools surfaced by attached MCP servers.</li>
    <li><strong>memory</strong> — read and write the local memory store.</li>
    <li><strong>todo</strong> — structured per-session todo list, surfaced to the model and the UI.</li>
    <li><strong>goal</strong> — declare and update long-running goals (see Goal mode).</li>
    <li><strong>subagent</strong> — spawn a child agent to handle a delimited subtask.</li>
    <li><strong>download</strong> — fetch a remote artifact into the workspace.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Permissions</h2>
  <p>
    Tools that mutate state or run code can require user approval. When the model invokes
    one, the runner emits a permission request event. The active transport (TUI, ACP,
    app-server) decides how to surface that to the user, then sends the resolution back.
  </p>

  <p>
    For headless flows, <code>--auto-approve</code> short-circuits permission requests so
    the agent runs without interactive consent. Use it deliberately.
  </p>

  <h2>Adding tools</h2>
  <p>
    Tools implement a small Go interface (name, schema, invoke). Once registered, they are
    available to every provider through the tool registry — no per-provider plumbing needed.
    For tools you don't want to write in Go, expose them via an MCP server instead.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Built-in vs MCP.</strong> Built-in tools live in the binary and have direct
    access to workspace state. MCP tools are processes; they're isolated and easy to ship
    independently.
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
